# Config for whoever is DEPLOYING, not for the server being deployed to. Lives on your dev/
# control machine only, next to Deploy-DayZServer.ps1 — never rsynced to the server (excluded
# the same way host.env is) and never committed. host.env is the opposite: config the SERVER
# renders into itself. The two don't mix — see docs/CONFIGURATION.md.
#
# ONE FILE PER ENVIRONMENT: copy this to `deployer.prod.env` (the VPS) and/or
# `deployer.staging.env` (the local QEMU VM — DEPLOY_REMOTE_HOST=staging-vm, the ssh alias
# from staging/New-StagingVm.ps1). Deploy-DayZServer.ps1 -Env picks the file; bare runs
# default to STAGING, prod must be explicit. The mirror-pull tools (Sync-*, Pull-*) always
# read deployer.prod.env — the repo mirrors track prod only. KEY=VALUE, one per line.
# (Bare `deployer.env` is still read as a legacy name for prod.)

# Which host to ssh/rsync to. No default — Deploy-DayZServer.ps1 (without -Local),
# and Pull-DayZServer.ps1 all refuse to run without it (or an
# explicit -RemoteHost). Not needed at all when running with -Local (i.e. on the server itself).
DEPLOY_REMOTE_HOST=your-host

# SSH login user. Defaults to "ubuntu" in every script if omitted — only set this if yours
# differs.
#DEPLOY_REMOTE_USER=ubuntu
